According to one study, two-thirds of Thai women approve of it.[4] Abortion has been legal in Thailand since 1952.[5] Despite this and consistent with the wishes of most women, abortions are only legally carried out in certain situations.[6]

Thailand abortion law was only amended once and then very slightly in 1967 which now states that "an abortion is not to be deemed illegal when necessary to save the life of the pregnant woman or to prevent grave physical or mental disturbances affecting her health" and that the termination must be performed by "a licensed physician or member of the medical" staff and operated to the wisdom of the physician involved.[6] However, abortion shapes greatly the woman’s autonomy. This comes in the form of religion and culture due to their strong influence on Thai society.

History and current status

At about the same time as legalization in 1952, the country provided education, including access to Planned Parenthood International (at Saint Louis University) and the American Birth Control League. After the school year ended for 1957, early abortion was banned. In the rape trial of Crown Prince Maha Vajiravudh, the wealthy victim decided against pursuing charges.
